ODE XXII. vo‘rivn INSCRIPTION To DIANA.

Nothing more need be said of this ode than that it is one of the votive inscriptions common among the ancients, and that a pine-trec would be very fittingly dedicated to Diana. The attempts made to extract a story out of the occasion and the offering are preposterous. That which is chiefly noticeable in this and other poems by Horace, more or less similar, is the rare and admirable merit of terseness. The poet has sufficient reliance on himself to be sure that, how- ever briefly and simply he expresses himself on a subject to which brevity and simplicity belong, his unmistakable mark will appear on the work. ⁵
